<subSubSection id="FCC6650FFFFEFFB7DF26ED9D9953F97A" pageId="21" pageNumber="211" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="B4633684FFFEFFB7DF26ED9D9855FAE0" blockId="21.[862,1366,1261,1283]" box="[862,1366,1261,1283]" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">
<heading id="EF2B81E8FFFEFFB7DF26ED9D9855FAE0" box="[862,1366,1261,1283]" centered="true" fontSize="8" level="2" pageId="21" pageNumber="211" reason="8">
<taxonomicName id="73DC4D07FFFEFFB7DF26ED9D9855FAE0" authority="(WAGNER, 1842)" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[862,1366,1261,1283]" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Monodelphis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="21" pageNumber="211" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="domestica">
<emphasis id="86A8EA96FFFEFFB7DF26ED9D998DFAE2" box="[862,1166,1262,1283]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">MONODELPHIS DOMESTICA</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="D04D4B75FFFEFFB7D8E7ED9E984DFAE0" author="Wagner A" box="[1183,1358,1261,1283]" pageId="21" pageNumber="211" pagination="356 - 362" refId="ref24975" refString="Wagner A. 1842. Diagnosen neuer Arten brasilischer Saugthiere. Archiv Naturgeschichte 8: 356 - 362." type="journal article" year="1842">WAGNER, 1842</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B4633684FFFEFFB7DF5EEC679953F97A" blockId="21.[806,1422,1299,1903]" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">
Our molecular analyses showed a close proximity between 
<taxonomicName id="73DC4D07FFFEFFB7DFE9EC409924FAA4" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[913,1063,1330,1352]" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Monodelphis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="21" pageNumber="211" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="domestica">
<emphasis id="86A8EA96FFFEFFB7DFE9EC409924FAA4" box="[913,1063,1330,1352]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">M. domestica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the remaining species of the 
<taxonomicName id="73DC4D07FFFEFFB7DF2FEC229912FA85" authorityName="Erxleben" authorityYear="1777" box="[855,1041,1361,1382]" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Monodelphis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="21" pageNumber="211" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brevicaudata">
<emphasis id="86A8EA96FFFEFFB7DF2FEC229912FA85" box="[855,1041,1361,1382]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">M. brevicaudata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
complex, supporting the recent inclusion of this species in the complex by 
<bibRefCitation id="D04D4B75FFFEFFB7D931EC1C9E72FA47" author="Solari S" pageId="21" pageNumber="211" pagination="317 - 333" refId="ref24362" refString="Solari S. 2010. A molecular perspective on the diversification of short-tailed opossums (Monodelphis: Didelphidae). Mastozoologia Neotropical 17: 317 - 333." type="journal article" year="2010">Solari (2010)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName id="73DC4D07FFFEFFB7DFF3ECFD99A6FA40" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[907,1189,1422,1443]" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Monodelphis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="21" pageNumber="211" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="domestica">
<emphasis id="86A8EA96FFFEFFB7DFF3ECFD99A6FA40" box="[907,1189,1422,1443]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">Monodelphis domestica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from the remaining analysed species of the 
<taxonomicName id="73DC4D07FFFEFFB7D8ACECDE988EFA22" authorityName="Erxleben" authorityYear="1777" box="[1236,1421,1452,1474]" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Monodelphis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="21" pageNumber="211" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brevicaudata">
<emphasis id="86A8EA96FFFEFFB7D8ACECDE988EFA22" box="[1236,1421,1452,1474]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">M. brevicaudata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
complex by the relatively larger size and the dorsal fur entirely grey, without orange or reddish flanks. Owing to the external similarities between 
<taxonomicName id="73DC4D07FFFEFFB7D961EF7A9E53F9DF" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1842" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Monodelphis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="21" pageNumber="211" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="domestica">
<emphasis id="86A8EA96FFFEFFB7D961EF7A9E53F9DF" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">M. domestica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="73DC4D07FFFEFFB7D82AEF5499C6F9DF" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[1106,1221,1575,1596]" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Monodelphis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="21" pageNumber="211" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="glirina">
<emphasis id="86A8EA96FFFEFFB7D82AEF5499C6F9DF" box="[1106,1221,1575,1596]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">M. glirina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the eastern bank of the Xingu river (which exhibit upperparts greyish), we provide external and cranial comparisons between these two forms.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FCC6650FFFFEFFB4DF47EFD29C92FD26" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="212" pageId="21" pageNumber="211" type="description">
<paragraph id="B4633684FFFEFFB4DF47EFD29FECFE0C" blockId="21.[806,1422,1299,1903]" lastBlockId="22.[164,779,198,709]" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="212" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">
Externally, 
<taxonomicName id="73DC4D07FFFEFFB7DFB7EFD19966F955" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[975,1125,1697,1719]" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Monodelphis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="21" pageNumber="211" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="domestica">
<emphasis id="86A8EA96FFFEFFB7DFB7EFD19966F955" box="[975,1125,1697,1719]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">M. domestica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has smaller, narrower, and more whitish feet, with paler dorsal scales covered with white (versus cream or greyish) hairs. Caudal scales are also lighter in 
<taxonomicName id="73DC4D07FFFEFFB7D8E2EF8D9833F8F1" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[1178,1328,1789,1811]" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Monodelphis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="21" pageNumber="211" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="domestica">
<emphasis id="86A8EA96FFFEFFB7D8E2EF8D9833F8F1" box="[1178,1328,1789,1811]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">M. domestica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, mainly ventrally, and caudal hairs are more visible without magnification, giving a hairy aspect to the tail. In 
<taxonomicName id="73DC4D07FFFEFFB7DF5EEE2A9EBFF88D" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[806,956,1881,1902]" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Monodelphis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="21" pageNumber="211" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="domestica">
<emphasis id="86A8EA96FFFEFFB7DF5EEE2A9EBFF88D" box="[806,956,1881,1902]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="211">M. domestica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the mid-dorsum is grey and the laterals are also grey or tend to be yellowish, whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="73DC4D07FFFDFFB4DCDCE9969C14FF1A" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[164,279,228,250]" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Monodelphis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="22" pageNumber="212" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="glirina">
<emphasis id="86A8EA96FFFDFFB4DCDCE9969C14FF1A" box="[164,279,228,250]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="212">M. glirina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the general colour is darker, with middorsum grey or dark grey and the laterals tending to light orange. In 
<taxonomicName id="73DC4D07FFFDFFB4DD17E8519F06FED4" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[367,517,290,311]" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Monodelphis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="22" pageNumber="212" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="domestica">
<emphasis id="86A8EA96FFFDFFB4DD17E8519F06FED4" box="[367,517,290,311]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="212">M. domestica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, there is a yellowish circumocular area that contrasts with the blackish eyelids. In 
<taxonomicName id="73DC4D07FFFDFFB4DD45E8139CB3FE97" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[317,432,351,373]" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Monodelphis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="22" pageNumber="212" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="glirina">
<emphasis id="86A8EA96FFFDFFB4DD45E8139CB3FE97" box="[317,432,351,373]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="212">M. glirina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the circumocular area is greyish and does not contrast with the eyelids. Additionally, we found seven mammae in 
<taxonomicName id="73DC4D07FFFDFFB4DE0DE8EE9E08FE52" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[629,779,412,434]" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Monodelphis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="22" pageNumber="212" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="domestica">
<emphasis id="86A8EA96FFFDFFB4DE0DE8EE9E08FE52" box="[629,779,412,434]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="212">M. domestica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(specimens LZUFPI 158, MPEG 34994), but nine in 
<taxonomicName id="73DC4D07FFFDFFB4DCDCE8A99C14FE0D" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[164,279,473,495]" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Monodelphis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="22" pageNumber="212" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="glirina">
<emphasis id="86A8EA96FFFDFFB4DCDCE8A99C14FE0D" box="[164,279,473,495]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="212">M. glirina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(specimens MPEG 1318, 10134, 38985).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B4633684FFFDFFB4DCC4E88B9C92FD26" blockId="22.[164,779,198,709]" pageId="22" pageNumber="212">
Cranially, 
<taxonomicName id="73DC4D07FFFDFFB4DD45E88A9CD0FDEE" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[317,467,504,526]" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Monodelphis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="22" pageNumber="212" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="domestica">
<emphasis id="86A8EA96FFFDFFB4DD45E88A9CD0FDEE" box="[317,467,504,526]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="212">M. domestica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is generally larger. The interorbital region is narrower and more pronounced, which is readily seen in dorsal view; the rostrum is proportionally shorter; the maxillopalatine fenestrae are broader; the posterolateral palatal foramen is larger; and the palatal region is slightly more expanded backward.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
